qas.question: What did the Renaissance in Asia usher in?

plausible_answers.text: Johannes Gutenberg developed a printing press

qas.question: Who did not develop the printing press?
What education did not spread across the globe?
Who delivered new ideas to other civilizations?

context: The Renaissance in Europe ushered in <b0_0>a new age of scientific and intellectual inquiry<b0_0/> and appreciation of ancient Greek and Roman civilizations. Around 1450, <b1_0><b2_0>Johannes Gutenberg<b2_0/> developed a printing press<b1_0/>, which allowed works of literature to spread more quickly. The European Age of Empires saw European ideas of education in <b3_0>philosophy, religion, arts and sciences<b3_0/> spread out across the globe. <b4_0>Missionaries and scholars<b4_0/> also brought back new ideas from other civilisations — as with the Jesuit China missions who played a significant role in the transmission of knowledge, science, and culture between China and Europe, translating works from Europe like Euclid's Elements for Chinese scholars and the thoughts of Confucius for European audiences. The Enlightenment saw the emergence of a more secular educational outlook in Europe.
